 Insight into the Struggle for Recognition of Estonians' WWII Memories in Europe / rMelchior, Inge -- tRed Carnations on Victory Day and Military Marches on UPA Day? Remembered History of WWII in Ukraine / rYurchuk, Yuliya -- tPart 4: Memorial Media Spaces -- tFraming the Ukrainian Insurgent Army and the Latvian Legion: Transnational History-Writing on Wikipedia / rKaprāns, Mārtiņš -- tNegotiating Memory in Online Social Networks: Ukrainian and Ukrainian-Russian Discussions of Soviet Rule and Anti-Soviet Resistance / rKulyk, Volodymyr -- tFootball and Memories of Croatian Fascism on Facebook / rAndersen, Tea Sindbæk -- tCollective Memory and Institutional Reform in Albania / rGjevori, Elvin -- tClashes between National and Post-national European Views on Commemorating the Past: The Case of the Centennial Hall in Wrocław / rPietraszewski, Igor / Törnquist-Plewa, Barbara -- tNotes on contributors -- tIndex of names -- tSubject index  aThe world wars, genocides and extremist ideologies of the 20th century are remembered very differently across Central, Eastern and Southeastern Europe, resulting sometimes in fierce memory disputes. This book investigates the complexity and contention of the layers of memory of the troubled 20th century in the region. Written by an international group of scholars from a diversity of disciplines, the chapters approach memory disputes in methodologically innovative ways, studying representations and negotiations of disputed pasts in different media, including monuments, museum exhibitions, individual and political discourse and electronic social media. Analyzing memory disputes in various local, national and transnational contexts, the chapters demonstrate the political power and social impact of painful and disputed memories. The book brings new insights into current memory disputes in Central, Eastern and Southeastern Europe. It contributes to the understanding of processes of memory transmission and negotiation across borders and cultures in Europe, emphasizing the interconnectedness of memory with emotions, mediation and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aCollective memoryxPolitical aspects. 0aEmotionsxPolitical aspects. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspects. 4a20. Jahrhundert. 4a20th century. 4aCentral, Eastern and South-Eastern Europe. 4aErinnerungskultur. 4aErinnerungspolitik. 4aMemory disputes. 4aOsteuropa. 4aZentraleuropa. 4amemory politics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aSindbæk Andersen, Tea, eeditor.1 aTörnquist-Plewa, Barbara, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831104533480 cprintz978311043763840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110453539zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110453539.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DKUb2016